absurd.\n  //\n  // For large search spaces, we need a smarter approach.\n  // However, for the toggle case (p=2), we can enumerate if numFree <= ~25.\n  // For numFree > 25 with p=2, we use meet-in-the-middle.\n  //\n  // For general p with many free variables, we need an optimization approach.\n  // Since each pivot variable is a linear function of the free variables,\n  // the total cost is also a linear function mod p of the free variables\n  // (kind of — it's sum of mod-reduced values, which is not linear over integers).\n  //\n  // Actually, let's think more carefully. With p=2, each variable is 0 or 1,\n  // and cost = number of 1s. With larger p, cost = sum of values.\n  //\n  // For p=2: we want minimum Hamming weight solution.\n  // For general p: we want minimum sum solution.\n  //\n  // For the constraints given (up to 40 buttons, 40 lights), the rank of the\n  // system is at most 40, so we could have up to 40 free variables in degenerate\n  // cases. But in practice, the number of free variables is usually small.\n  //\n  // Strategy: enumerate if p^numFree <= threshold, otherwise use\n  // meet-in-the-middle for p=2 or heuristic for larger p.\n\n  const totalCombinations = Math.pow(p, numFree);\n\n  if (totalCombinations <= 1_000_000) {\n    return enumerateFreeSolutions(aug, nCols, p, pivotCol, pivotRow, freeVars, currentRow);\n  }\n\n  // Meet-in-the-middle for p=2 with many free variables\n  if (p === 2) {\n    return meetInTheMiddleBinary(aug, nCols, pivotCol, pivotRow, freeVars, currentRow);\n  }\n\n  // For large p with many free variables (unlikely given constraints), fall back\n  // to trying each free variable = 0 (which gives a valid but possibly non-optimal solution)\n  return enumerateFreeSolutions(aug, nCols, p, pivotCol, pivotRow, freeVars, currentRow);\n}\n\nfunction computeSolution(\n  aug: number[][],\n  nCols: number,\n  p: number,\n  pivotCol: number[],\n  pivotRow: number[],\n  freeVars: number[],\n  freeAssignment: number[],\n  c